[[Category:Geography terminology]] {{Geo-term-stub}}

The '''SK-42 reference system''' also known as the [[Feodosy Krasovsky|Krasovsky]] 1940 [[Reference ellipsoid|ellipsoid]], is a coordinate system established in the [[Soviet Union]] in 1942 as ''Systema koordinat'' ({{lang-ru|Система координат 1942 года}}), and provides parameters which are linked to the geocentric [[Cartesian coordinate system]] [[PZ-90]]. It was used in geodetic calculations, notably in military mapping and determining state borders.<ref>slide 11, Borodko</ref>

The Krasovsky 1940 ellipsoid uses a [[semi-major axis]] (equatorial radius) {{math|''a''}} of 6,378,245&nbsp;m, and an inverse flattening {{math|1/''f''}} of 298.3.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Office|first1=United States Naval Observatory Nautical Almanac|last2=Office|first2=Great Britain Nautical Almanac|title=Explanatory Supplement to the Astronomical Almanac|date=2005|publisher=University Science Books|isbn=9781891389450|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uJ4JhGJANb4C|language=en}}</ref>{{rp|220}}

