[[Major-General]] '''Sir Thomas Aiskew Larcom, 1st Baronet''' [[Privy Council of Ireland|PC]] [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (24 December 1801 – 15 June 1879) was a leading official in the early [[Ordnance Survey Ireland|Irish Ordnance Survey]] that started in 1824. He later became a poor law commissioner, census commissioner and finally executive head of the British administration in Ireland as [[Under Secretary for Ireland|under-secretary]] to the [[Lord-Lieutenant of Ireland]], a position the government of the day was eager for him to take.

The longest-serving under-secretary (1853–1868), and a man of unusual abilities, Larcom had a distinguished career in his adopted country and acted with an impartiality that won him respect from all parties. In 1868 he was admitted to the [[Irish Privy Council]] and created a Baronet.

